description:
The Third Amendment Act, 1954, amended the Constitution of India to update population limits used for parliamentary seat delimitation and expanded the Union's control over certain trade and commerce.

Key points:
- Article 81(1)(b) was amended to relax the population limits for parliamentary constituencies, changing the minimum and maximum population per seat from 500,000–750,000 to 650,000–850,000, reflecting the 1951 census data and allowing proper delimitation within the constitutional cap of 500 Lok Sabha members.
- The Seventh Schedule (List III - Concurrent List), entry 33, was amended to extend Union control over trade and commerce in:
  (a) Products of any industry declared by Parliament to be under Union control in public interest, including imported goods of the same kind;
  (b) Foodstuffs, including edible oils and oilseeds;
  (c) Cattle fodder, including oilcakes and concentrates;
  (d) Raw cotton (ginned or unginned) and cotton seeds;
  (e) Raw jute.

This amendment addressed constitutional challenges related to representation based on census updates and enhanced the Union's regulatory authority over essential agricultural and industrial products.

Date enacted: 22nd February, 1955.

Introduced by: C.C. Biswas, 19th May, 1952.
